Here are the **most common and recommended ways** in late 2025 to create a clean GitHub repository for a **Solana** project using the official SDKs (mostly **Anchor** which is still the #1 choice for 90%+ of developers).

### Option 1: Quickest & Recommended (Anchor + Modern CLI) â€” 1 minute setup

```bash
# 1. Make sure you have the latest tools (as of Dec 2025)
cargo install --git https://github.com/coral-xyz/anchor anchor-cli --locked --force
# or just use npm if you prefer (newer way)
npm install -g @solana-program/create

# 2. Create project + git repo in one go (recommended!)
pnpm create solana-program my-cool-solana-app counter
# or with npm
npx @solana-program/create@latest my-cool-solana-app counter

# 3. Go inside & push to GitHub
cd my-cool-solana-app
git init
git add .
git commit -m "Initial commit: Solana Anchor counter program"

# Create repo on GitHub (via browser or gh cli)
gh repo create --public --source=. --remote=origin
# or manually: https://github.com/new â†’ create repo â†’ copy url

git branch -M main
git push -u origin main
```

This creates a modern project structure with:

```
my-cool-solana-app/
â”œâ”€â”€ programs/
â”‚   â””â”€â”€ counter/
â”‚       â”œâ”€â”€ src/
â”‚       â”‚   â””â”€â”€ lib.rs           â† your program logic
â”‚       â””â”€â”€ Cargo.toml
â”œâ”€â”€ Anchor.toml                      â† config
â”œâ”€â”€ Cargo.toml                       â† workspace
â”œâ”€â”€ package.json                     â† for TS tests/client
â”œâ”€â”€ ts/
â”‚   â””â”€â”€ tests/                       â† mocha + @coral-xyz/anchor tests
â””â”€â”€ .gitignore
```

### Option 2: Classic Anchor Way (still very popular)

```bash
# Create project
anchor init my-solana-counter

# Enter & prepare git
cd my-solana-counter
git init
git add .
git commit -m "feat: initial Anchor Solana program"

# Create empty repo on GitHub and push
git remote add origin https://github.com/yourusername/my-solana-counter.git
git branch -M main
git push -u origin main
```

### Option 3: Native Rust (no Anchor) â€” when you want maximum control / minimal dependencies

```bash
# Create folder & init git
mkdir solana-native-hello && cd solana-native-hello
git init

# Create basic structure
cargo init --lib programs/hello
cd programs/hello

# Update Cargo.toml
# Add these under [dependencies]
solana-program = "2.1"           # check latest version on crates.io
borsh = "1.5"
borsh-derive = "1.5"

# src/lib.rs - minimal hello world program
```

```rust
use solana_program::{
    account_info::AccountInfo,
    entrypoint,
    entrypoint::ProgramResult,
    msg,
    pubkey::Pubkey,
};

entrypoint!(process_instruction);

pub fn process_instruction(
    _program_id: &Pubkey,
    _accounts: &[AccountInfo],
    _instruction_data: &[u8],
) -> ProgramResult {
    msg!("Hello Solana! (native Rust program)");
    Ok(())
}
```

Then commit & push as usual.

### Quick Recommendation Table (Dec 2025)

| Style                 | Speed to start | Best for                          | GitHub Popularity | Recommended?     |
|-----------------------|----------------|-----------------------------------|-------------------|------------------|
| `pnpm create solana-program` | â˜…â˜…â˜…â˜…â˜…         | New projects, modern stack        | Very high         | **Yes #1**      |
| `anchor init`         | â˜…â˜…â˜…â˜…          | Classic Anchor users              | Still very high   | Yes             |
| Native Rust           | â˜…â˜…            | Learning, minimal deps, performance | Medium            | Only if needed  |
| Steel / other frameworks | â˜…â˜…â˜…         | Experimental / specific needs     | Low               | No (for most)   |

Pick **Option 1** if you're starting fresh â€” it's the cleanest and most up-to-date way right now.

